<item>
  <title>Ax–Grothendieck Theorem</title>
  <link>https://sheafofthoughts.org/posts/ax-grothendieck.html</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<section id="introduction" class="level1">
<h1>Introduction</h1>
<p>We all know from basic linear algebra that injective endomorphisms of a finite-dimensional vector space are also surjective. The same holds for finite sets. Over algebraically closed fields, there is an analogous result:</p>
<div id="thm-ax-special" class="theorem">
<p><span class="theorem-title"><strong>Theorem 1 (Special case of Ax–Grothendieck Theorem)</strong></span> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> be an algebraically closed field, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%5Cin%20%5Cmathbb%7BN%7D">, and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f_1,%5Cdots,f_n%5Cin%20k%5Bx_1,%5Cdots%20,x_n%5D">. If the map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0AF:k%5En%20%5Crightarrow%20k%5En,%20%5Cqquad%20F(%5Cunderline%7Bx%7D)=(f_1(%5Cunderline%7Bx%7D),%5Cdots,%20f_n(%5Cunderline%7Bx%7D))%0A"> is injective, then it is surjective.</p>
</div>
<p>We will talk about an analogous and more general statement about schemes later on.</p>
<p>Let us comment briefly on the hypotheses. Injectivity is the correct assumption for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F">: the map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?z%5Cmapsto%20z%5E2"> is surjective but not injective on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BC%7D">. Furthermore, the result is generally false for non-algebraically closed fields; for example, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20%5Cmapsto%20x%5E3"> is injective but not surjective on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BQ%7D">.</p>
<p>As a sanity check, let’s verify the result for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n=1">. Consider a polynomial <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f%5Cin%20k%5Bx%5D"> such that the map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%5Cmapsto%20f(x)"> is injective; then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> can have at most one root. Since <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> is algebraically closed, it follows that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f=ax+b"> with <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?a%5Cneq%200"> (otherwise the map would not be injective). Hence <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> is surjective.</p>
<p>Moreover, the theorem is easy to prove when <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k=%5Coverline%7B%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D%7D_p">.</p>
<div class="proof">
<p><span class="proof-title"><em>Proof</em> (For <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k=%5Coverline%7B%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D%7D_p">). </span>Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%20z:=(z_1,%5Cdots,%20z_n)%5Cin%20k%5En"> and let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L"> be the subfield of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> generated by the coefficients of the polynomials defining <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> and by the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?z_i">’s. The field <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L"> is a finite extension of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_p">, hence a finite set. The restriction <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F:L%5En%5Crightarrow%20L%5En"> is well-defined and injective; since <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5En"> is finite it is also surjective. Therefore, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%20z"> lies in the image of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F">, proving the claim.</p>
</div>
<hr>
</section>
<section id="proof-of-the-theorem" class="level1">
<h1>Proof of the theorem</h1>
<p>We start by proving two lemmas and then proceed with the proof of Theorem&nbsp;1.</p>
<div id="lem-criterion-injectivity" class="theorem lemma">
<p><span class="theorem-title"><strong>Lemma 1 (Lemma)</strong></span> The map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> is injective if and only if there exist <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?q_%7Bi,j%7D%5Cin%20k%5Bx_1,%5Cdots,x_n,y_1,%5Cdots,y_n%5D"> and integers <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k_j%3E0"> such that, defining <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0Ag_i(x_1,%5Cdots,%20x_n,y_1,%5Cdots,y_n)%0A:=f_i(x_1,%5Cdots%20,%20x_n)-f_i(y_1,%5Cdots,y_n),%0A"> for all <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?j"> we have the identity <span id="eq-g-criterion"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5En%20g_i%5Ccdot%20q_%7Bi,j%7D=(x_j-y_j)%5E%7Bk_j%7D%0A%5Ctag%7B1%7D"></span></p>
</div>
<div class="proof">
<p><span class="proof-title"><em>Proof</em>. </span>Consider the ideal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?I=(g_1,%5Cdots,%20g_n)">. The map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> is injective if and only if all the zeros of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?I"> are of the form <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(%5Cunderline%7Bx%7D,%5Cunderline%7Bx%7D)"> for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%7Bx%7D%5Cin%20k%5En">. This is the case if and only if the zeros of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?I"> are a subset of the zeros of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?J=(x_1-y_1,%5Cdots,x_n-y_n)">, i.e.&nbsp;if and only if <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathrm%7BV%7D(I)%20%5Csubseteq%20%5Cmathrm%7BV%7D(J)">. By the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_Nullstellensatz">Hilbert Nullstellensatz</a>, this holds if and only if <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?J%20%5Csubseteq%20%5Csqrt%20I">; hence <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(x_j-y_j)%5Cin%20%5Csqrt%7BI%7D">.</p>
</div>
<div id="lem-no-preimage" class="theorem lemma">
<p><span class="theorem-title"><strong>Lemma 2 (Lemma)</strong></span> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%7Bz%7D%5Cin%20k%5En">. Then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%20z"> is not in the image of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> if and only if there exist <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?r_1,%5Cdots%20,r_n%5Cin%20k%5Bx_1,%5Cdots%20,x_n%5D"> such that <span id="eq-r-criterion"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5En%20r_i%5Ccdot%20(f_i-z_i)=1.%0A%5Ctag%7B2%7D"></span></p>
</div>
<div class="proof">
<p><span class="proof-title"><em>Proof</em>. </span>The element <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%7Bz%7D"> is not in the image of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> if and only if the ideal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?I=(f_1-z_1,%5Cdots,f_n-z_n)"> has no zeros, equivalently <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1%5Cin%20I"> (again by Nullstellensatz).</p>
</div>
<p>Now we are ready to prove the theorem.</p>
<div class="proof">
<p><span class="proof-title"><em>Proof</em> (Of Theorem&nbsp;1). </span>Suppose <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%7Bz%7D%5Cin%20k%5En"> is not in the image of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F">. Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A"> be the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D">-algebra generated by:</p>
<ul>
<li>the coefficients of the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f_i">’s defining <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F">;</li>
<li>the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?z_i">’s;</li>
<li>the coefficients of the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?q_%7Bi,j%7D"> as in Lemma&nbsp;1;</li>
<li>the coefficients of the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?r_i"> as in Lemma&nbsp;2.</li>
</ul>
<p>Since finitely many coefficients are involved, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A"> is of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D">. Moreover, the restriction <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F:A%5En%20%5Crightarrow%20A%5En"> is still injective. Furthermore, we have the following identities in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A%5Bx_1,%5Cdots,x_n,y_1,%5Cdots,y_n%5D"> given respectively by Lemma&nbsp;1 and Lemma&nbsp;2: <span id="eq-criterion-1"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5En%20g_i%5Ccdot%20q_%7Bi,j%7D=(x_j-y_j)%5E%7Bk_j%7D%0A%5Ctag%7B3%7D"></span></p>
<p><span id="eq-criterion-2"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5En%20r_i%5Ccdot%20(f_i-z_i)=1%0A%5Ctag%7B4%7D"></span></p>
<p>Now pick a maximal ideal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?m"> in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A">. The field <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A/m"> is finite by the following claim.</p>
<div class="claim">
<p><a id="clm-nullstellensatz-Z"></a> <strong>Claim:</strong> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B"> be an algebra of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D">. If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?m"> is a maximal ideal of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B">, then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B/m"> is a finite field.</p>
</div>
<p>Assuming the claim, set <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L=A/m"> and note that the reduction <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BF%7D:L%5En%5Crightarrow%20L%5En"> of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> modulo <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?m"> is injective. Indeed, consider <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%20x,%5Cunderline%20y%5Cin%20L%5En"> such that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BF%7D(%5Cunderline%20x)=%5Coverline%7BF%7D(%5Cunderline%20y)">. By evaluating Equation&nbsp;3 at <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(%5Cunderline%20x,%5Cunderline%20y)"> we obtain <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%20x=%5Cunderline%20y"> in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5En">, since <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%20g_i(%5Cunderline%20x,%20%5Cunderline%20y)=0"> for all <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i">.</p>
<p>Since <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5En"> is finite and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BF%7D"> is injective, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%20F"> is surjective. However, reducing <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cunderline%7Bz%7D"> modulo <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?m"> and evaluating Equation&nbsp;4 at a preimage of that reduction under <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%20F"> yields a contradiction. Hence, up to proving the claim, we have established Theorem&nbsp;1.</p>
<div class="proof">
<p><span class="proof-title"><em>Proof</em> (Proof of the Claim). </span>To prove the claim, consider two cases:</p>
<ul>
<li>If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?m%5Ccap%20%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D=p%20%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D">, then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B/m"> is an algebra of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_p">; by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zariski%27s_lemma">Zariski’s lemma</a> <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B/m"> is a finite extension of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_p">, hence finite.</li>
<li>If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?m%5Ccap%20%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D=0">, then in the tower <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D%20%5Csubset%20%5Cmathbb%7BQ%7D%20%5Csubset%20B/m">, we see that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B/m"> is of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BQ%7D">, hence is finite over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BQ%7D"> by Zariski’s lemma. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artin%E2%80%93Tate_lemma">Artin–Tate’s lemma</a> then implies that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BQ%7D"> would be of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D">, a contradiction.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
</section>
<section id="generalization-to-schemes" class="level1">
<h1>Generalization to schemes</h1>
<p>Note that the map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> considered in Theorem&nbsp;1 can be seen as the map induced on closed points by a morphism of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-schemes <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BA%7D%5En_k%5Crightarrow%20%5Cmathbb%7BA%7D%5En_k">. This leads to the following question:</p>
<div id="qst-example">
<p><strong>Question:</strong></p>
<p>Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> be an algebraically closed field and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X"> a scheme of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">. If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f:X%5Crightarrow%20X"> is a <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-endomorphism injective on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-points, is it surjective on all points?</p>
</div>
<p>The finite-type assumption is necessary: the map induced by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0Ak%5BX_1,%5Cdots,%20X_n,%5Cdots%5D%5Cto%20k%5BX_1,%5Cdots,%20X_n,%5Cdots%5D%0A"> sending <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X_1%5Cmapsto%200"> and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X_i%5Cmapsto%20X_%7Bi-1%7D"> for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i%3E1"> is injective but not surjective.</p>
<p>The answer is positive, and it follows (not trivially) from the following theorem.</p>
<div id="thm-ax-groth" class="theorem">
<p><span class="theorem-title"><strong>Theorem 2 (Ax–Grothendieck Theorem)</strong></span> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S"> be a scheme and let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X"> be a scheme of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S">. Any injective <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S">-endomorphism <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f:X%5Crightarrow%20X"> is bijective.</p>
</div>
<p>Moreover, if <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X"> is reduced and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> is an algebraically closed field of characteristic <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?0">, then an injective endomorphism on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-points is in fact an isomorphism (not merely a bijection). This is not trivial since we have bijective morphisms of schemes that are not isomorphisms (for example the one induced by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k%5Bt%5E2,t%5E3%5D%5Crightarrow%20k%5Bt%5D">). A reference for this is Lemma 1 of <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/4097654">this article</a>.</p>
<p>We will not give a proof of Theorem&nbsp;2; see J. Ax’s paper <a href="https://projecteuclid.org/journals/pacific-journal-of-mathematics/volume-31/issue-1/Injective-endomorphisms-of-varieties-and-schemes/pjm/1102978046.full">Injective endomorphisms of varieties and schemes</a>, or Grothendieck’s version in <a href="https://www.numdam.org/item/PMIHES_1966__28__5_0/">EGA IV<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?_3">, Proposition 10.4.11</a> for a complete proof.</p>
<p>Let us explain why Theorem&nbsp;2 implies that injectivity on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-points gives surjectivity on all points.</p>
<p>The first ingredient is Chevalley’s theorem on constructible sets (see Hartshorne, Ex. II.3.19).</p>
<div id="thm-chevalley" class="theorem">
<p><span class="theorem-title"><strong>Theorem 3 (Chevalley’s theorem)</strong></span> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f:X%5Cto%20Y"> be a finite type morphism between noetherian schemes. If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Z%20%5Csubseteq%20X"> is a constructible subset (i.e.&nbsp;a finite union of locally closed subsets), then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(Z)"> is constructible.</p>
</div>
<p>The following lemma explains why Theorem&nbsp;2 implies Theorem&nbsp;1.</p>
<div id="lem-universally-injective" class="theorem lemma">
<p><span class="theorem-title"><strong>Lemma 3 (Lemma)</strong></span> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X,%20Y"> be schemes of finite type over an algebraically closed field <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">. Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f:X%5Cto%20Y"> be a morphism whose restriction to <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-points <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0Af:%20X(k)%5Cto%20Y(k)%0A"> is injective. Then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> is universally injective.</p>
</div>
<p>Assuming this lemma, consider a morphism <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f:%5Cmathbb%7BA%7D%5En_k%5Cto%20%5Cmathbb%7BA%7D%5En_k"> over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> which is injective on closed points (which are exactly the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-points, since <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> is algebraically closed). Then in particular <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> is injective on all points. From Theorem&nbsp;2 we get the surjectivity of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> on all points (answering the question raised before) and in particular also surjectivity on closed points, since only closed points are sent to closed points. In particular, we obtain Theorem&nbsp;1.</p>
<div class="proof">
<p><span class="proof-title"><em>Proof</em> (Of Lemma&nbsp;3). </span>Observe that the diagonal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f:X%5Cto%20X%5Ctimes_Y%20X"> is of finite type. Indeed, it is locally of finite type because <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X%5Cto%20%5Cmathrm%7BSpec%7D(k)"> is locally of finite type (and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f"> can be seen as the first factor of this map), and it is quasi-compact because <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X"> is noetherian (being of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">).</p>
<p>Moreover, the diagonal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f"> is surjective on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-points. Indeed, for any <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-point of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X%5Ctimes_Y%20X"> given by a morphism <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Cpsi:%20%5Cmathrm%7BSpec%7D(k)%5Cto%20X%5Ctimes_Y%20X%0A"> we can consider the diagram</p>
<!-- https://q.uiver.app/#q=WzAsNSxbMCwwLCJcXG1hdGhybXtTcGVjfShrKSJdLFsxLDEsIlhcXHRpbWVzX1kgWCJdLFsyLDEsIlgiXSxbMSwyLCJYIl0sWzIsMiwiWSJdLFsxLDJdLFswLDIsIlxccGhpXzIiLDAseyJjdXJ2ZSI6LTN9XSxbMSw0LCIiLDIseyJzdHlsZSI6eyJuYW1lIjoiY29ybmVyIn19XSxbMiw0XSxbMyw0XSxbMSwzXSxbMCwzLCJcXHBoaV8xIiwyLHsiY3VydmUiOjN9XSxbMCwxLCJcXHBzaSIsMl1d -->
<iframe class="quiver-embed" src="https://q.uiver.app/#q=WzAsNSxbMCwwLCJcXG1hdGhybXtTcGVjfShrKSJdLFsxLDEsIlhcXHRpbWVzX1kgWCJdLFsyLDEsIlgiXSxbMSwyLCJYIl0sWzIsMiwiWSJdLFsxLDJdLFswLDIsIlxccGhpXzIiLDAseyJjdXJ2ZSI6LTN9XSxbMSw0LCIiLDIseyJzdHlsZSI6eyJuYW1lIjoiY29ybmVyIn19XSxbMiw0XSxbMyw0XSxbMSwzXSxbMCwzLCJcXHBoaV8xIiwyLHsiY3VydmUiOjN9XSxbMCwxLCJcXHBzaSIsMl1d&amp;embed" width="524" height="432" style="border-radius: 8px; border: none;">
</iframe>
<p>and by injectivity of the morphism <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X%5Cto%20Y"> we obtain <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cphi_1=%5Cphi_2"> as maps of topological spaces. They are also the same on the structure sheaf, because <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> is algebraically closed. Therefore, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cphi_1=%5Cphi_2">, which means that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cpsi"> factorizes through the diagonal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f">.</p>
<p>Furthermore, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X%5Ctimes%20_Y%20X"> is a <a href="https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/005T">Jacobson</a> scheme (i.e.&nbsp;its underlying topological space is Jacobson) because it is of finite type over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">, and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> is Jacobson. By Theorem&nbsp;3 the set <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f(X)"> is constructible. Consider <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Z:=(X%5Ctimes_Y%20X)%5Csmallsetminus%20%5CDelta_f(X)">. This is constructible and every closed point of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X%5Ctimes_Y%20X"> lies inside <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f(X)"> (by surjectivity of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f"> on closed points). Since every nonempty constructible subset in a Jacobson scheme contains a closed point, it follows that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Z=%5Cemptyset">. Therefore, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f"> is surjective on all points.</p>
<p>Now we prove that the surjectivity of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f"> implies the universal injectivity of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f">. Indeed, consider any <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g:%20Z%5Cto%20Y"> and the diagonal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5CDelta:%20X%5Ctimes_Y%20Z%5Cto%20(X%5Ctimes_Y%20Z)%5Ctimes_Z(X%5Ctimes_Y%20Z)%0A"> of the base change. This diagonal map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta"> is surjective because it is the base change of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f">, which is surjective. Thus, we are reduced to proving that surjectivity of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f"> implies injectivity of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> (the same will then hold for any base change).</p>
<p>Consider <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_1,x_2%5Cin%20X"> with <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(x_1)=f(x_2)=:y">. We can find a field <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L"> such that the following diagram commutes: <!-- https://q.uiver.app/#q=WzAsNCxbMCwxLCJrKHkpIl0sWzEsMCwiayh4XzEpIl0sWzEsMiwiayh4XzIpIl0sWzIsMSwiTCJdLFswLDFdLFswLDJdLFsyLDNdLFsxLDNdXQ== --> <iframe class="quiver-embed" src="https://q.uiver.app/#q=WzAsNCxbMCwxLCJrKHkpIl0sWzEsMCwiayh4XzEpIl0sWzEsMiwiayh4XzIpIl0sWzIsMSwiTCJdLFswLDFdLFswLDJdLFsyLDNdLFsxLDNdXQ==&amp;embed" width="440" height="432" style="border-radius: 8px; border: none;"></iframe></p>
<p>We get the following commutative diagram: <!-- https://q.uiver.app/# --> <iframe class="quiver-embed" src="https://q.uiver.app/#&amp;embed" width="528" height="432" style="border-radius: 8px; border: none;"></iframe></p>
<p>By surjectivity of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f"> we can find <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%5Cin%20X"> such that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta_f(x)"> is the image of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cepsilon">, hence we get <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_1=x_2">. This shows that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> is injective, and therefore universally injective.</p>
</div>
<p>Note that the complex-geometric picture does not match the algebraic one. For example, there are holomorphic maps <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BC%7D%5En%5Crightarrow%20%5Cmathbb%7BC%7D%5En"> that are injective but not surjective. However, this cannot happen for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n=1">, as one can show that all holomorphic injective maps <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f:%20%5Cmathbb%7BC%7D%5Crightarrow%20%5Cmathbb%7BC%7D"> are of the form <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f=ax+b">; see the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casorati%E2%80%93Weierstrass_theorem">Casorati–Weierstrass theorem</a>.</p>
<hr>
</section>
<section id="conclusion" class="level1">
<h1>Conclusion</h1>
<p>To conclude, we point your attention to the fact that this theorem is linked to a famous conjecture, namely the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobian_conjecture">Jacobian conjecture</a>.</p>
<div id="cnj-jacobian" class="theorem conjecture">
<p><span class="theorem-title"><strong>Conjecture 1 (Jacobian conjecture)</strong></span> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> be a field of characteristic <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?0"> and let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F:%20k%5En%5Cto%20k%5En"> be a polynomial mapping. If the Jacobian determinant <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?J_F"> is invertible, then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?F"> is an isomorphism.</p>
</div>
<p>Over an algebraically closed field of characteristic <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?0">, the fact that the bijection in Theorem&nbsp;2 becomes an isomorphism shows that, to prove the Jacobian conjecture for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BA%7D%5En_k">, it suffices to show that a map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0AF:%5Cmathbb%7BA%7D%5En_k%5Crightarrow%20%5Cmathbb%7BA%7D%5En_k%0A"> with invertible Jacobian determinant is injective.</p>
<hr>
<p>I would like to thank my friend who suggested this topic to me and helped me write this post.</p>
<hr>
</section>
